{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17401"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71634"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10091"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7316"},{"type":"tags","id":"7319"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71634"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe erector spinae muscle group forms a prominent vertical mass in the deep back region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arrangement of muscles within the erector spinae group?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Two parallel columns: multifidus and spinalis","Two diagonal columns crossing at the midline","Three parallel columns: iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis","Four parallel columns: iliocostalis, longissimus, spinalis, and rotatores","Single column with segmental attachments"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe erector spinae consists of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree parallel columns: iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis \u003C/strong\u003E(Image). These muscles run vertically along the length of the vertebral column, with iliocostalis being most lateral, longissimus intermediate, and spinalis most medial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo parallel columns: multifidus and spinalis\u003C/strong\u003E - The multifidus is a separate deep back muscle and not part of the erector spinae group\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo diagonal columns crossing at the midline\u003C/strong\u003E - The columns run parallel and do not cross\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFour parallel columns: iliocostalis, longissimus, spinalis, and rotatores\u003C/strong\u003E - The rotatores are separate deep back muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle column with segmental attachments\u003C/strong\u003E - This does not accurately describe the three-column arrangement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe erector spinae muscles are the primary extensors of the vertebral column. When acting bilaterally they extend the spine, and when acting unilaterally they assist in lateral flexion to the same side.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The erector spinae muscles consist of three parallel columns: iliocostalis (lateral), longissimus (intermediate), and spinalis (medial).","The erector spinae muscles are the primary extensors of the vertebral column.","The erector spinae muscles are located in the deep back, lateral to the spinous processes."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cErector Spinae\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray389.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21320"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21320"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zi3DPSu3ybWjf5UMZNsMhGTisydJaW.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zi3DPSu3ybWjf5UMZNsMhGTisydJaW.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":1207}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T21:03:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T12:11:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10091"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71634"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonym